{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_iotite_ver01/data/sn84020064/00542866408/1930032101/0010.xml":{"full_text":"TEN\nLISTENING IN'\n\n6:M to 7:00 P. M\nConcert Orr he stra-Jessie* Dragon\neUe and the Cavaliers\nJessica Dragonette will sing \"Ro\nmance\" and Love Is a Story That\u2019s\nOld\u201d as her soprano solos over the\nNBC system from 6:00 to 7:00\nOClOCit.\nSixteen number will be offered\nduring the course of this hours\nprogram, with the entire ensemble\nspotted during the middle of the of\nfering 'in gems from \"Bunny Side\nUp.\u201d Thi program will come Io a\nClos? with Miss Dragonette. the\nCavaliers and the orchestra singing\nand playing that perennial favorite.\n\"When You and I Were Young.\nMaggie.\"\nHere are the details:\nOrchestra \u2014Ma rc h.\nOrchestra\u2014Badinage Herbert\nCavaliers\u2014Happy Days Are Here\nA^tlh\nSoprano solo \u2014Romance. Donaldson\nOrchestra\u2014Trees Rasbach\nSoprano and teno- duet\u2014All for\nYsU\u2014 Princess Pat\" Herbert\nOrchestra\u2014Soliloquy ..Bloom\ntnsemble Gems \u201cSunny Side\nUp\" Henderson\nVocgJjiolo\u2014Three for Jack.. Squires\nBess-cinrinct solo\u2014Jalousie.... Gade\nOrchestra\u2014Ave Marie Gounod\nCavaliers\u2014Lady Be Good. Gershwin\nOrchestar\u2014My Inspiration Is You\nNichols\nSoprano solo\u2014Love Is a Story\nThat\u2019s Old\u2014\" Madcap Duchess\u201d\nHerbert\nOrchestra\u2014 Harmonia Harry. Baxter\nOrchestra, soprano and Cavaliers\u2014\nWhen You and I Were Young,\nMaggie.\n7:30 to 8:00 P. M-\nOrchestra and Chorus\nMusical selections played by an\norchestra under Josef Koestner\u2019s di\nreettan and sung by a mixed chorus\nwill be heard in the broadcast from\nChicago through the NBC system\nbetween 7:30 and 8:00 o\u2019clock.\n10:00 to 10:30 P. M.\nPiano Pictures\nTwenty fingers will race over the\nblack and white keys of two concert\ngrand pianos in the presentation of\n\"Pfknp Pictures\" by Phyllida Ash\nley and Aileen Fealy over the NBC\nsystem tonight from 10:00 to 10:30\no'clock.\nOut of the six numbers to be\nplayed by this feminine piano team.\n\u201cMinuet and Gavotte\u201d by Saint-\nSaens is the only unfamiliar offer\ning. Originally written for a string\nquartet by the French composer, it\nis one of the most successful num\nbers ever adapted for two-piano in\nterpretation. It has a decided\nmelody of extreme beauty.\nHere is the complete program:\nMinuet and Gavotte...Saint-Saens\nNight on the Bald rdountam\n7^. Moussorgsky\nRosemunde Ballet Schubert\nKamennoi-Ostrow Rubinsteir\nCapaice Viennois Kreisler\nPrelude in G Minor.. .Rachmaninofi\n10:30 to 11:00 P. M.\n.Hill Billy Boys\nOle-time songs that lend them\nselves well to simple interpretation\nby harmonica, banjo, guitar, accor\ndioj^and voice will be played and\nsung by the Hill Billy Boys during\nthOir program over the NBC sys\nterpTrom 10:30 to 11:00 o\u2019clock.\n11:00 to 11:30 P. M.\nAces of Harmony\nA r vocal trio consisting of men all\nof whom are soloists in their own\nright .will harmonize for the enter\ntainment of NBC system listeners\nduring the Aces of Harmony period\ntonight from 11:00 to 11:30 o\u2019clock.\n11:30 to 12:00 P. M.\nPacific Nomads\nMelody will carry the Pacific\nNomads into foreign lands once\nmore when they broadcast through\nNBC stations tonight between 11:30\nand 12:00 o\u2019clock.\nCharles Hart will direct the string\nand -woodwind ensemble and Lucile\nI: Menus for the Family I\nBY SISTER MARY\nSEA Hervice Writer\nNEW discoveries mid theories\nabout foods are being present\ned to- the housewife almost dally\nand sometimes. in her conscien\ntious attempt to apply them to her\nown needs, she becomes puzzled\nand.wonders how she can know\nwhat js Hcienaiflrally proper and\ncorrect and what Is taboo.\nResearch workers and inveati\ngatpre in foods and nntrltlon are\n<-pnMae(j.v working to verify ex\nperiments and establish definite\nresults. The doubt about some\nfoods seems to be well cleared\n\u25a0way and facts may be accepted\nToast, that breadstuff which is\nso popular nowadays from break\nfast to midnight lunch, has come\nunder the experimenter\u2019s eye. It\nhas been acknowledged for some\ntime that the heat of toasting acts\non the starch in the bread, chang\ning it to sugar and shortening the\ntime required for body digestion\nThe question recently has been\nwhether the effect of the toasting\nheat might not be so harmful to\nthe protein content of the bread\nthat the good effect on the starch\nmight be counteracted.\nTeets have proven that the pro\ntein of toasted bread is as com\npletely digested as the protein of\nuntoasted bread.\nI Dry toast is more readily digest\ned than soft toast because it re\nquires more chewing and breaks\ninto tiny particles. The process\nof digestion is started by the In\ncreased flow of naliva\nWhen bread is cut thick for\ntoasting and is buttered and close\nly, covered after toasting to keep\nit hot. all the points in favor of\ntoast are lost. The thickness of\nthe bread prevents the heat from\npenetrating and thoroughly effect\ning the change in the starch con\ntent. The steaming softens the\ntoast and destroys Its crispness\nBread should be cut in thin\nslices and toasted not too fast if\nfull benefit is to be had from its\ntoasting.\nKhtley soprano, will contribute two\nsolas during the following program:*\n1 Orchestra\u2014On the Grand Canal\nSchad\nOrchestra\u2014Di inane he de Mai....\nSoprano solo\u2014On Wings of Song\nMendelssohn\nI Orchestra\u2014Waltz from Serenade\nfor Strings Tchaikovsky\nSoprano solo\u2014Vous Dansez, Mar-\nquise Lena ire\nOrchestra\u2014Serenade Drlgo\nOrchestra\u2014Napolitana Istres\nRAIL EARNINGS\nCHICAGO. Ma-ch 20. Net in\ncome of the Chicago. Rock Island\nand Pacific Railroad company in\n1929 was 314.007.320. the largest in\nits history and 6 38 per cent higher\nthan the previous record year of\n1928. when earning totaled $13,167,-\n696\nThe company's annual report\nshowed a balance of $5,235,075 after\ndividends, which was invested in\nadditions and betterments to prop\nerty.\nFrisco Curb\nSAN FRANCISCO. March 20 r\u2014\nCuib traders took profits today\nalter recent market advances, and\ndepressed prices slightly. Activity\nwas well distributed as 24 893 shares\nchange: hands lor $264,307. Bond\ntrading absorbed 513.00 C.\nLittle evidence of trends in vari\nous groups appeared, with the ex\nception of continued fractional gains\nin the preferred utility stocks. The\ncnlj\u2019 closing price changes of more\nthan a point were Crown Wiliam *tte\npreferred seconds, up 8, Pacific\nCoast Biscuit preferred up 4*i and\nWaialua Agricultural company up\n2\u2019u. Improving business outlook on\na long-range view, with new finan\ncial adjustments and business alli\nance prospects boosted these issues.\nIntercoast had a morning flurry,\n3.063 shares being offered as the\nprice was bid up a fraction. The\nsupply was too great, and the gain\nwas converted into a thin loss.\nL. A. Stocks\nLOS ANGELES. March 20 1\nOils were generally lower but new\nhighs were reached in several other\nissues on the Los Angeles stock and\ncurb exchange today.\nTrans-America advanced to\n44% and Pacific Finance lost \u2019i to,\n38. both on good turnover. Los An-\ngeles Gas preferred jumped 3 points\nto a new peak at 106' i, as did Pa\ncific Lighting rights in climbing 15\ncents to 14.35 and Southern Cali\nfornia Edison 7 per cent preferred,\nin rising to 30%. Security-First\nNational Bank dropped 1% and Pa- 1\nciflc Public Service lost but San\nJoaquin Light prior preferred touch\ned a new high at 118%. In the oil\ngroup Union of California lost 1%,\nAssociates Standard Rio;\nGrande and Richfield\nDetroit Aircraft was a feature on\nthe curb, rising a point to 7%, a\nnew high. Samson Tira advanced\nof a point to $7. Fox Theatres\ndropped to 6\u20194 and a new low.\nFokker was up to 23% a new\npeak. New highs were also scored\nby Universal Consolidated Oil and\nPacific Indemnity. Other changes\nwere slight.\nGrain Market\nCHICAGO, March 20 UP>\u2014Lively\nupturns in wheat prices today re-\nsuited from aggressive buying, espe\ncially in the final transactions, the\nmarket closing firm at the day\u2019s top\nlevel. Half a dozen different Euro\npean countries were reported as\nhaving purchased at least some\nNorth American wheat today for\ntrans-Atlantic shipment. Unusual\nabsence of selling pressure here was\nnoted, and traders gave sharp at- j\ntention to chances that bulk of the I\nnew crop of domestic winter wheat\nwill be swept by a cold wave and\nbe caught devoid of any snow cover.\nClosing quotations on all grain\nwere strong, with wheat l%c to\n2%c a bushel higher than yester-\nday\u2019s finish. Corn closed %c to,\nl%c up. oats %c to %c advanced\nand provisions varying from 7c de\ncline to a rise of 2c.\nCorn and oats obtained their]\nstrength mostly from the action of\nwheat. Furthermore, unsettled\nweather which is forecast will tend\nto restrict still sharper the move-i\nment of corn to terminal markets, i\nProvisions averaged lower, respon\nsive to downturns in hog values\nCotton Market\nNEW YORK. March 20 ^\u2014Trad\ning in cotton was leas active Uday\nwith early advances on' covering and\ntrade buying followed by reactions\nunder renewed realizing which ap\npeared to be combined with some\nhedge selling. May contracts after\nselling up to 15.59 or 15 points net\nhigher, broke to approximately the\n15'* cent level but offerings were\nlight at the decline and later\nfluctuations were nervous and ir\nregular. The mid-afternoon market\nwas quiet and steady at net declines\nof some 3 to 5 points.\nSpot steady; middling. 15.50.\nClose:\nJanuary <old\u00bb. 15.83\nJanuary new). 15.58-59.\nMarch. 15.40.\nMay. 15.57-59\nJuly. 15.63-64.\nOctober (old), 15.58-60.\nOctober \u00bbnew>. 15.37-39.\nDecember (old), 15.74.\nDecember (new>, 15 58-59.\nNEW ORLEANS. March 20\nSpot cotton closed steady; 16 points\nup Sales. 238 bales; middling. 15.26\n\nALLOYS RESIST ACIDS\nNEW YORK <*>.\u2014One of the\nimportant uses of alloys is to re\nsist acid corrosion in chemisal man\nj ufacture. The most notable ex\nample of success, says a report by\nBurnham E. Field to the Amen\ncan Institute of Mining and Metal\nlurgical Engineers Is alloy of chro\nmium with iron or nickel to resist\nI nitric acid.\nDOUGLAS DAILY DISPATCH. FRIDAY MORNING, MARCH 21, 1930.\nWool Market S9M C FW,ru,r>\nBOSTON, March 20 Seles\nare being closed on finer grades\ncombing territory wools. Origin\nal bag 64s and fin., woo*s ol mostly\nFrench combing staples is bringing\n72 to 75 cents scoured basis. Graded\nrtrictly comblhg 75-60* is seHin\" at\n73 to 75 cents scoured basis. De\nmand cn these grades Is very light\nand sales scattered. Lower grades\nare very quiet.\n\nWall Street Briefs\nNEW YORK. March 20 \u2022-\u2022\u2022'\u2014The\nNew York federal reserve bank\u2019s\nweekly statement of gold move\nments at this port for the period\nending March 19. showed imports\nOf $5,331,000. of which $5,239 COO\ncame from Brazil and $92.C00 chiefly\nfrom other Latin-American coun\ntries. and exports of $20,000 to Ger\nmany There was no net change\ntn the amount of gyld earmarked\nfor foreign account.\nGeneral Motors dealers in the\nUnited States last month delivered\n88.742 cars to consumers, compar\u2019d\nwith 110.148 for February a year\nago. Sales by General Motors man\nufacturing divisions to dealers in\nthe country last month amounted\nto 100.901 cars against 141.422 in\nFebruary. 1929. Total sales to deal\ners. including Canadian sales and\noverseas shipments, amounted to\n126.196 cars contrasted with 175.148\nin February last year.\nNet operating income of the\nChesapeake and Ohio railway for\nFebruary totaled $5,861,770, com-\nwent)\nCINA.LLV\ni cou.eero\u00df M J\nUone fl\nnr? .fl p\nFRECKLES AND HIS FRIENDS\nTODAY\u2019S 7UE FIRST K ,Yl\nDAY OP A\nENGM SMELL A DIFFERENCE\nIW THE AR TOSU. J\nMAkE A FELLA FEEL Ji Q\nU& 6STTINS UP EARLY Gk J;\nin tue mornns a j-yf\nwks'/ y\nMOM\u2019N POP